{"cursor":"7412","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn mathematics and physics, a 'scalar field' associates a scalar value to every\npoint in a space. The scalar may either be a mathematical number, or a physical\nquantity. Scalar fields are required to be coordinate-independent, meaning that\nany two observers using the same units will agree on the value of the scalar\nfield at the same point in space (or spacetime). Examples used in physics\ninclude the temperature distribution throughout space, the pressure distribution\nin a fluid, and spin-zero quantum fields, such as the Higgs field. These fields\nare the subject of scalar field theory\n","linknr":247,"url":"Scalar_field","recorded":1362534999,"links":46,"instances":["physics","geometry","special_relativity","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Quantum field theory","Multivariable calculus"],"headings":["Definition","Uses in physics","Other kinds of fields","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Scalar_field.png/220px-Scalar_field.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/3/7/837ad824da9e7fe007e6d30ad64dbd5d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/4/9d43cb8bbcb702e9d5943de477f099e2.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["scalar","mathematics"],["scalar","mathematics"],["scalar","physics"],["distribution","mathematics"],["observer","special_relativity"],["vector","geometry"]],"members":["scalar","vector","observer","distribution"],"related":["Mathematics","Physics","Scalar_(mathematics)","Scalar_(mathematics)","Scalar_(physics)","Temperature","Pressure","Higgs_field","Scalar_field_theory","Real-valued_fun